    <glossary>
        <definition id="import-auto-id1195741"><term>torque</term> <meaning id="fs-id1448566">the turning effectiveness of a force</meaning></definition>
            <definition id="import-auto-id1868981"><term>rotational inertia</term> <meaning id="fs-id3080979">resistance to change of rotation. The more rotational inertia an object has, the harder it is to rotate</meaning></definition>
                <definition id="import-auto-id2384482"><term>moment of inertia</term> <meaning id="fs-id3354053">mass times the square of perpendicular distance from the rotation axis; for a point mass, it is <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mtext>mr</m:mtext></m:mstyle><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>  and, because any object can be built up from a collection of point masses, this relationship is the basis for all other moments of inertia</meaning></definition>
    </glossary>
